| footnote=Population 1880<U+2013>1970.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The United States Census Bureau|url=http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0027.html|title=Population of the 100 largest cities 1790-1990|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref><br> Population 1980<U+2013>2000<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The United States Census Bureau|url=http://www.census.gov/population/censusdata/c1008090pc.txt|title=1980-1990 Population of Places With 100,000 or More Inhabitants|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref>}}

In the city the population was spread evenly between all age groups. The median age was 34 years. About 13% of families and 19% of the population were below the [[poverty line]]. Most of Erie's people are of European dissent.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=helloerie.com|url=http://www.helloerie.com/Social.cfm|title=Erie Social and Demographic Information|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref>

Since the mid 1990s, the International Institute of Erie (IIE), founded in 1919, has helped with the resettlement of refugees from [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]], [[Eritrea]], [[Ghana]], [[Iraq]], [[Kosovo]], [[Liberia]], [[Somalia]], [[Sudan]], the former [[Soviet Union]], and [[Vietnam]]. The inclusion of refugees in Erie's community augments religious diversity and prompts community events like cultural festivals.<ref>{{citeweb|publisher=International Institute of Erie|url=http://www.interinsterie.org|title=International Institute of Erie&ndash;Home|accessdate=2007-06-15}}</ref>

In the early 20th century, Erie had a significant [[Russia]]n immigrant community, many of whom worked in the [[shipbuilding]] plants along the bayfront. Unusual for a Great Lakes city, a substantial number of these Russian immigrants were [[Old Believer]]s. Even today, the gold-domed  Church of the Nativity,<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.churchofthenativity.net|title=Church of the Nativity|accessdate=2007-05-25}}</ref> on the bayfront near the former heart of the Russian community, is an Old Believer church.<ref>{{citeweb|publisher=Russian Orthodox Outside Russia|url=http://www.russianorthodoxchurch.ws/english/pages/firsttier/diocesesbishops.html|title=Russian Orthodox Bishops|accessdate=2007-05-26}}</ref>Bishop Daniel of Erie, of the [[Russian Orthodox Church Outside Russia]], is based in Erie and is the Vicar President of the Synod of Bishops for the Old Believers.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.orthodoxwiki.org/Daniel_(Alexandrow)_of_Erie/|title=Daniel Alexandrow on Orthodox Wiki|accessdate=2007-05-26}}</ref>[[Image:Mercyhurst2.jpg|thumb|left|Catholic influence is felt beyond the parish in Erie; here, at entrance to Mercyhurst College.]]

Erie has a [[Jewish]] community that is over one hundred fifty years old. [[Temple Anshe Hesed]], a member of the [[Union for Reform Judaism]], is served by its spiritual leader, Rabbi John L. Bush.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.taherie.org/|title=Tah Erie|accessdate=2007-05-26}}</ref> Erie is home to the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Erie]], covering 13&nbsp;counties (9,936&nbsp;sq&nbsp;mi- the largest in the state). Its diocesan seat is the [[St. Peter Cathedral, Erie|Saint Peter Cathedral]] in Erie, which has a {{convert|265|ft|m}} central tower flanked by two {{convert|150|ft|m}} towers. It is among the tallest churches in the U.S and was constructed in 1873. 

According to the Association of Religion Date Archives,<ref>The ARDA Database has no precise figures on the membership of African American churches, so it provides an estimate of 25,000&nbsp;members. The two Russian orthodox churches list no membership numbers. The Salvation Army lists over 4,000 members. Jews were under a thousand and Quakers showed no membership.[http://www.thearda.com/mapsReports/reports/counties/42049_2000.asp]Retrieved on [[June 1]], [[2007]].</ref> Erie County had a total 2000 population of 280,843&nbsp;persons, of which 103,333 claimed affiliation with the Catholic church, 40,301 with mainline Protestant houses of worship, and 12,980 with evangelical Protestant churches.

==Economy==
{{main|Economy of Erie, Pennsylvania}}
[[Image:Eriefactory01.jpg|thumb|right|Old factory in Erie]]

Erie is the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania's primary access point to [[Lake Erie]], the Great Lakes, and the [[Saint Lawrence Seaway]]. The city emerged as a maritime center after the [[American Revolution]], then as a railroad hub during the great American westward expansion. Erie became an important city for iron and steel manufacturing during the [[Industrial Revolution]] and thrived well into the 20th century with big industry. 

While only electric [[locomotive]] building remains of the large manufacturers in the early 21st century, a more diverse mix of mid-sized industries has emerged. This broader economic base includes not only smaller and more agile steel and plastic plants, but also a vigorous service sector: health, insurance and tourism thrive in Erie. As of March 2007, Erie's unemployment rate was 4.1%, more than a point's improvement over the 5.2% rate a year earlier.<ref>{{cite web|first=Lou|last=Baxter|date=[[May 1]], [[2007]]|publisher=YourErie.com|url=http://www.wjettv.com/content/fulltext/?cid=2114|title=Erie Unemployment Falls |accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> The national unemployment rate was 4.4%.
[[Image:Eriebeach33.jpg|thumb|left|Beaches impact local economy]]
Erie is the corporate headquarters of [[GE Transportation Systems]], Plastek Industries, and [[Erie Insurance Group]].  Lord Corporation was founded in and has major operations in Erie.<ref>{{cite web|last=McNeel|first=Rick |url=http://www.lord.com/tabid/2952/Default.aspx|publisher=LORD Corporation|title=LORD History|accessdate=2007-05-25}}</ref> Over 10% of the nation's plastics are manufactured or finished in Erie-based plastics plants.<ref name="city facts"/> Erie is an emerging center for biofuels and environmental research; the city produces over 45 million gallons of biofuel a year.<ref>{{cite news| last=Carroll| first=Jim| publisher=Erie Times-News| date=[[2006-07-06]]| title=Biodiesel could fuel economy| url=http://www.goerie.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060706/NEWS02/607060400&SearchID=73286058459115 |accessdate=2007-07-02}}</ref> Tourism plays an increasingly important role in the local economy with over 4 million people visiting [[Presque Isle State Park]] and other attractions. Canadian shoppers regularly frequent the [[Millcreek Mall]] and [[Peach Street]] stores and attractions.

The city government is encouraging development through the implementation of selected Commonwealth programs that encourage residents, universities and businesses to contribute towards the community<U+2019>s [[economic]] health.<ref>{{cite news| last=Palatiella| first=Ed| title=Revised LERTA plan: Shorten program, target blighted areas| date=[[2007-05-06]]| publisher=Erie Times-News| pages=1A, 8A}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=YourErie.com|last=Sillvio|first=Matt|url=http://www.wjettv.com/content/fulltext/?cid=2074|title=Mayor Announces Lerta Plan|date=[[April 27]],[[2007]]|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref>

In 2002, the Erie Downtown Improvement District (DID) contracted a [[Philadelphia]]-based company (Kise, Straw, and Kolodner) to set up a "master plan" for the city of Erie's downtown.<ref>{{cite news| last=Miller| first=George| date=[[2007-05-15]]| publisher=Erie Times-News|url=http://www.goerie.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2007703150396|title=Erie Builds Master Plan|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> The DID plan includes the construction of mid-rise and high-rise structures, which will be utilized primarily for housing and retail expansion in the city centre. Plans include renovating historical downtown buildings, including the Boston Store and Mercantile Building. Fourth River Development and Radnor Property Group were selected as the developers.

== Healthcare and utilities ==
[[Image:Hamotheart.jpg|thumb|right|Hamot Heart Institute]]
Erie is a regional leader in health care with two of its hospitals being ranked nationally.<ref name="mul">{{cite web|publisher=Saint Vincent Health System|url=http://www.saintvincenthealth.com/about/history.htm|title=Saint Vincent History|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref><ref name="multy">{{cite web|publisher=Hamot Medical Center|url=http://www.hamot.org/a_AH_awards.php|title=Hamot Awards&Reconigtion|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> St. Vincent Health System was founded in 1875 as St. Vincent's Hospital, Erie's first medical institution, by the [[Sisters of St. Joseph]] and the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Erie]]. It was chartered by the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania in 1895 as the St. Vincent's Hospital Association. A school of nursing was established in 1901. Formal instruction of interns began in 1914. In 1981, St. Vincent's became the largest hospital in Pennsylvania, and one of the first hospitals in the country, to use computers to make medical records available to authorized personnel for patient treatment. St. Vincent Health Center became a subsidiary of St. Vincent Health System when the corporation was reorganized in 1988.<ref name="mul"/>The Erie Shriners Hospital for Children has been operating in Erie since 1927.<ref>{{citeweb|publisher=Shriners|url=
http://www.shrinershq.org/Hospitals/Erie/|title=Erie Shriners Hospital|accessdate=2007-06-12}}</ref> It won a 2007 achievement award from the [[Hospital and Healthsystem Association of Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{citeweb|publisher=HHAP|url=http://www.haponline.org/community_health/awards/2007/details.asp?ID=5aKYRU7SHXHLd9h1COE9|title=2007 HAP Achievement Award Winners|accessdate=2007-06-12}}</ref>  

One of Erie's largest employers, [[Hamot Medical Center]] has consistently been ranked as one of the best hospitals in the country.<ref name="multy"/> Pierre Simon Vincent Hamot (died in 1846) was a successful local Erie businessman whose homestead was donated by his descendants for the founding in 1881 of the Hamot Hospital Association. The medical center, along with the Hamot Heart Institute (pictured on right), are part of the Hamot Health Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Hamot Medical Center|url=http://www.hamot.org/a_AH_history_foundingOfHamot.php|title=Detailed History of Hamot|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref>

Hamot and St. Vincent organized two joint projects in the 1980s. The Tri-State Regional Trauma Center opened in 1983. The Regional Cancer Center (TRCC), founded in 1987, is one of the largest free-standing community cancer treatment centers in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trcc.org/|title=The Regional Cancer Centers Home Page|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref>

The [[Erie Water Works]], which was incorporated in 1865 as the Erie Water and Gas Company, includes a reservoir, two water treatment plants, and an elaborate water works and pipe network that provides water for most of the city and suburbs. PennElec, a [[First Energy]] Company provide electricity to the region, as well as the Northwestern Pennsylvania Rural Electric Company. [[Time Warner Cable]] serves as the region's cable provider after Adelphia was taken over by Time Warner.

Sewage service is provided by the Erie Sewer Authority. Many outlining townships have partnerships with the Sewer Authority to provide sewage service to their residents. It cleans about 30&ndash;40 million gallons of wastewater everyday.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The City of Erie|url=http://www.ci.erie.pa.us/Departments/SewerDepartment/tabid/74/Default.aspx|title=Erie Sewer Department|accessmonthday=May 21|accessyear=2007}}</ref>

==Arts and culture==
[[Image:1920warner.gif|thumb|left|The Warner Theatre]]Erie is home to several professional and amateur performing-arts groups. The most significant is the [[Erie Philharmonic]], in continuous existence since 1913 (with the exception of an [[interregnum]] during [[World War II]]). This group of professional musicians also has a full [[Choir|chorus]] and a Junior Philharmonic division which actively tours the area.

The Lake Erie Ballet is a professional company which performs well-known ballets throughout the year.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.lakeerieballet.org|title=Lake Erie Ballet|accessdate=2007-05-25}}</ref> The Erie Civic Music Association attracts, sponsors, and books performances by professional musicians, singers, entertainers, and ensembles from the world over.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.eriecivicmusic.com/|title=Erie Civic Music Association|accessdate=2007-05-25}}</ref> The [[Erie Art Museum]] is the city's main [[art gallery]], located in a former [[Custom house|U.S. Customs House]] on lower State Street near the bayfront. Its collection has a particular emphasis on [[folk art]] and [[modern art]]. It also hosts a popular [[blues]] and [[jazz]] concert series.

Downtown Erie's historic and ornate [[Warner Theatre]] hosts performances by the three groups. Renovated in the 1980s and again in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[WSEE-TV]]|url=http://www.goerie.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070323/WSEE01/70322036&SearchID=73279381497185|title=Warner Renovations Unveiled|date=[[March 23]], [[2007]] |accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> the Warner serves as the hub of Erie's [[Louis J. Tullio Arena|Civic Center]]. The downtown area is the home of the Erie Playhouse, one of the leading community theaters in the country, as well as the Roadhouse Theatre for Contemporary Art, home to more avant-garde works.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.roadhousetheatre.org|title=The Roadhouse Theater for Contemporary Art|accessdate=2007-05-25}}</ref> The local Great Lakes Film Association (GFLA), which hosts the annual Great Lakes Independent Film Festival every fall, was founded in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Great Lakes File Festival|url=http://www.greatlakesfilmfest.com/|title=Great Lakes Film Association|accessdate=2007-06-25}}</ref>[[Image:Bostonstore.jpg|thumb|The iconic Boston Store in Downtown Erie]]


Along West 6th Street is Millionaires Row, a collection of 19th century [[Victorian architecture|Victorian]] mansions. The [[Erie Land Light|oldest lighthouse]] on the Great Lakes stands at the foot of Lighthouse Street.<ref>{{citeweb|publisher=The National Park Service|url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/maritime/light/erieland.htm|title=Inventory of Historic Light Stations Pennsylvania Lighthouses&ndash;Erie Land Lighthouse|accessdate=2007-05-30}}</ref> The lighthouse was built in 1818 and replaced in 1867.

The [[Bicentennial Tower]], located on Dobbins Landing at the foot of State Street, was built in 1995 to honor the city's 200th year. Construction was finished in 1996. It is 187&nbsp;feet tall and gives a panoramic view of Lake Erie and downtown. The Blasco Library and Erie Maritime Museum are its neighbors to the east. [[Presque Isle Downs]] opened for business on [[February 28]], [[2007]], the fourth slots parlor in the state and the first in western Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Erie Area Convention and Visitors Bureau|url=http://www.goerie.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070315/VISITERIE03/70315023&SearchID=73279381858352|title=Whats Ne&ndash;Presque Isle Downs|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> There are 2,000 slot machines as of opening day, and the adjoining racetrack is scheduled to open in September 2007.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=MTR Gaming|url=http://presqueisledowns.com/about/index.html|title=Presque Isle Downs Racing Overview|accessmonthday=May 21|accessyear=2007}}</ref>

== Sports ==
[[Image:ErieUht.jpg|thumb|right|Jerry Uht Park from the first-base side, overlooking downtown Erie.]]
Erie has had a long history of competitive sports. District 10 High Schools sports are played in the area, often with very close scores. Throughout history, Erie has had various semi-pro and professional sports teams. The city host's the nationally recognized [[McDonald's Classic]].<ref>{{citeweb|last=Webb|first=Dennis|url=http://www.bloggernews.net/13316|title=Erie Host's McDonald's Classic|accessdate=2007-05-25|publisher=Blogger News }}</ref> The area is home to [[General McLane High School]], who won both the State Football Championship and Basketball Championship in the same year, a first in the state.<ref>{{citeweb|last=Armas|first=Genaro|url=http://blog.pennlive.com/pasports/2007/03/general_mclane_57_greencastle.html|title= General McLane Beats Greencastle Antrim|publisher=PennLive|accessdate=2007-05-25}}</ref>

Erie hosts the [[Erie Freeze]]; a member of the [[American Indoor Football Association]] and the [[Erie Illusion]]; a member of the [[National Women's Football Association]]. The [[Erie Otters]] play hockey in the [[Ontario Hockey League]], and the [[Erie SeaWolves]] play double A baseball in the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]]; as an affiliate of the [[Detroit Tigers]]. Football and Hockey games are played at [[Louis J. Tullio Arena]], and The SeaWolves play at [[Jerry Uht Park]]. The various high school and collegiate teams play at various venues around the city, including Veterans Stadium.

==Recreation==
{{seealso|List of city parks of Erie, Pennsylvania}}
Erie's location along the shores of [[Lake Erie]] provides a plethora of outdoor activities throughout the year. The region's largest attraction is [[Presque Isle State Park]], drawing over 4 million visitors a year. The region grows grapes and produces the 3rd largest amount of wine in the [[United States]].<ref name="county facts"/> The area sports arenas [[Jerry Uht Park]] (the home of the [[Erie Seawolves]]), and [[Louis J. Tullio Arena]] (the home of the [[Erie Otters]] and [[Erie Freeze]]). 
[[Image:erieland.jpg|thumb|left| Erie Land Lighthouse]]
Erie is home to Presque Isle, a National Landmark.<ref name="bob"/> The [[Seaway Trail]] runs  through downtown Erie along the lakefront. The [[Tom Ridge Environmental Center]], at the foot of Presque Isle, features 7,000 square feet (650&nbsp;m<U+00B2>) of exhibit space.<ref>{{citeweb|publisher=Tom Ridge Environmental Center|url=http://www.trecpi.org/features.html|title=TREC Features|accessdate=2007-05-25}}</ref>

Historical sites also draw people to Erie. [[Union Station (Erie)|Union Station]] and the [[Warner Theatre (Erie, Pennsylvania)|Warner Theatre]] are historical buildings still in use. The Erie Playhouse is the third oldest community theater but it is the most active in the United States.<ref name="gene">{{Citation | first =Erie Area Convention and Visitors Bureau| title = ERIE 2007-2008 All Seasons Visitors Guide| place = Erie| year = 2007|}}</ref>
[[Image:Presque Isle Pennsylvania aerial view.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Presque Isle State Park. View is to the east-northeast.]]
Tourist destinations include many of the above, as well as the [[Bayfront Convention Center]]; the [[Bicentennial Tower]] that overlooks [[Lake Erie]]; Dobbins Landing, a pier in downtown Erie; the [[Erie Land Lighthouse]]; the [[Erie Maritime Museum]], the home port of the [[US Brig Niagara (replica)|US Brig ''Niagara'']]; [[Millcreek Mall]], the 11th largest shopping mall in the United States,<ref>{{citeweb|publisher=American Studies at Eastern Connecticut State University |url=http://www.easternct.edu/depts/amerst/MallsLarge.htm|title=List of Largest Shopping Malls in the United States|accessdate=2007-05-27}}</ref> [[Perry Square]], a large downtown park; [[Presque Isle Downs]], a racetrack and casino in Summit Township; [[Splash Lagoon]], the largest indoor waterpark on the East Coast and third largest in the United States;<ref name="gene"/> the [[Erie Zoo]], with its many animals and exhibits; and [[Waldameer Park|Waldameer Park and Water World]], a local amusement park.

==Law and government==
{{seealso|List of Mayors of Erie, Pennsylvania, United States|List of Burgesses of Erie, Pennsylvania}}
Erie city government consists of a [[mayor]] and [[city council]]. The mayor's office includes an elected city [[treasurer]] and city controller. Each of seven districts elects a representative to the city council. The membership select from within their ranks a city council president and vice president. Each member serves a two-year term. The mayor serves as [[chief executive]]; the city council prepares legislation and conducts oversight. The city council meets in Mario S. Bagnoni Council Chambers at [[City Hall]].
[[Image:ErieCtyCourthouse EriePA.JPG|thumb|Erie County Courthouse, Erie, Pennsylvania]] 
As of May 2007, Joseph Sinnott serves as mayor. (The incumbent, Rick Filippi, did not seek re-election in 2005 and is practicing law in Erie.) Susan DiVecchio serves as city treasurer.<ref>{{citeweb|publisher=City of Erie|url=http://www.erie.pa.us/Departments/CityTreasurer/tabid/66/Default.aspx|title=The City Treasurers Office|accessdate=2007-05-26}}</ref> Casimir J. Kwitowski is city controller. As of [[May]] [[2007]], the Erie City Council consists of: Rubye Jenkins-Husband (President), James N. Thompson, Patrick Cappabianca, Jessica Horan-Kunco, Curtis Jones, Jr., David Gonz<U+00E1>lez, and Joseph V. Schember.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=City of Erie|url=http://www.ci.erie.pa.us/CityCouncil/CityCouncilMembers/tabid/61/Default.aspx|title=Current Council Members|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref>

In exchange for taxes the city provides its residents with police and fire protection. For quarterly payments, the city provides garbage, recycling, water and sewer services. The city has come under criticism for cutting jobs in the public service sector, most in Police of Fire Departments.<ref name="jojo">{{citeweb|last=Bucsko|first=Mike|date=[[January 22]], [[2006]]|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06022/642210.stm|publisher=Pittsburgh Post Gazette|title=Erie cuts work force|accessdate=2007-06-29}}</ref>

Crime is enforced by the Erie Police Department. In 2005, six murders were committed in Erie, compared to one in 2004. Despite the rise in homicides, nonviolent crime in the city dropped by 14% percent in 2005 compared to 2004.<ref>{{citeweb|date=[[April 15]], [[2005]]|last=Hahn|first=Tim|url=http://www.goerie.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060614/NEWS02/606140482&SearchID=73285544078481|title= Chief:Erie still safe|publisher=[[Erie Times-News]]|accessdate=2007-06-29}}</ref> Since 2000, Erie has been experiencing a spike in drug crimes, which is due in part to a large decrease of Police Officers.<ref name="jojo"/> A link in the drug trade, Erie has strong criminal ties to [[Detroit]] and [[New York City]].<ref>{{citeweb|last=Abogast|first=Sarah|url=http://yourerie.com/content/fulltext/?cid=3266|date=[[June 28]], [[2007]]|title=Erie Drug Bust|publisher=Action News 24|accessdate=2007-06-28}}</ref> Erie is the home of many large drug busts, although Erie's crime rate is lower than the national average.<ref name="susan">{{citeweb|url=http://www.city-data.com/city/Erie-Pennsylvania.html|title=Erie Crime|publisher=City-data.com|accessdate=2007-06-29}}</ref> Erie's homicide rate per 100,000 residents increased from 1 in 2004 to 5.8 in 2005.<ref name="susan"/> The number of assaults in the city increased to 191 in 2005. Property crime, theft, arson, and burglaries were down in 2005 from 2004, rape was slightly higher.<ref name="susan"/>

==Education==
{{seealso|Colleges and universities of Erie}}
[[Erie City School District|Erie Public Schools]] enroll 12,527&nbsp;students in primary and secondary schools.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=GreatSchools.com|url=http://www.greatschools.net/cgi-bin/pa/district_profile/188/|title=Erie City School District Profile|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> The district has 23 public schools including elementary schools, middle schools, high schools, and one charter school. Other than public schools, the city is home to more than 40 private schools and academies including [[Cathedral Preparatory School]] and [[Mercyhurst Preparatory School]].
[[Image:Lecomerie.JPG|left|thumb|LECOM Main Campus]]
Erie's collegiate scene is fairy equally split between several colleges and universities. Created in the 1970s [[Penn State Erie, The Behrend College]] is the largest Penn State branch college.<ref name="penn">{{cite web|publisher=Penn State Erie|url=http://www.pserie.psu.edu/about.htm|title=About the College|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=Penn State Erie|url=http://www.erie.psu.edu/aboutPS/quickfacts.htm|title=2007 Enrollment Numbers|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> The university is noted for being one of the best value colleges in the country.<ref name="penn"/> 

Lake Erie College of Osteopathic Medicine (LECOM), a large medical campus located in Erie, with a branch in [[Bradenton, FL]], has one of the largest classes of medical students in the country.[[Image:brigniagara.JPG|thumb|The Erie Maritime Museum, Brig "Niagara", and Blasco Library.]]<ref>{{cite web|publisher=LECOM|url=http://www.lecom.edu/lecom/news/2009Arrives.asp|title=Welcome Largest Class of Medical Students|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> Other notable colleges in the Erie area include [[Mercyhurst College]], with the number one rated Division II lacrosse team in the US;<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Mercyhurst Athletics|url=http://hurstathletics.cstv.com/sports/m-lacros/spec-rel/050707aag.html|title=Lakers End Season Ranked No. 1|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> [[Allegheny College]], with one of the most beautiful campuses in the country;<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Allegheny College|url=http://www.allegheny.edu/visitors|title= Visitors Center, Most Beautiful Campus|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> [[Edinboro University of Pennsylvania]], a large college in nearby Edinboro, PA; and [[Gannon University]], a Catholic university in downtown Erie. Ranking officials of the City of Erie, Erie County, and the Erie School District began looking into the need for a [[community college]] in the Erie area in 2006.<ref>Flowers, Kevin, ''DiVecchio to Visit Community College'', Erie Times-News, 10 May 2007, pg 6B; Exploratory trips have included visits to [[Schnecksville, Pennsylvania#Schools|Lehigh Carbon Community College]] near [[Allentown, Pennsylvania]] in November 2006, and [[Sinclair Community College]] in [[Dayton, Ohio]] in May 2007.</ref>

The public libraries in Erie are part of the Erie County library system. The Raymond M. Blasco, M. D. Memorial Library, named for its benefactor, opened in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|Erie Library|publisher=Erie's Libraries|url=http://www.erielibrary.org/history.html|title=A Brief History of the Erie County Public Library|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> It is the third largest library in Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=City of Erie|url=http://www.ci.erie.pa.us/AboutErie/Facts/tabid/80/Default.aspx|title=Raymond M. Blasco Library|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> It is connected to the [[Erie Maritime Museum]], both of which are part of a bayfront improvement project that includes the [[Bayfront Convention Center]] and the [[Bicentennial Tower]].

== Transportation ==
{{main|Transportation of Erie}}
Erie's [[Metropolitan Planning Organization]] (MPO) generates an annual Erie Area Transportation Study for the [[Pennsylvania Department of Transportation]] (PennDOT). There are fifteen MPO's in the state, each consisting of local elected officials, representatives of major modes of transport, PennDOT officials, and others. Federal and State transportation regulations require urban areas of 50,000 or more in population to have an MPO, which is to do short-term (four years) and long-term (20+ years) transportation planning.<ref name="multiple">{{cite web|publisher=Pennsylvania DOT|url=ftp://ftp.dot.state.pa.us/public/Bureaus/Cpdm/STC/TransProgramLists/2007TYPNarrative.pdf|format=PDF|title=Pennsylvania's 2007 Transportation Program|date = [[August 3]] [[2006]]|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref>

[[Image:Bayfrontconnecterie.jpg|thumb|left|The Bayfront Connector connects I-90 with the waterfront.]]
Erie is well connected to the [[Interstate Highway System]]. Six highway exits from [[Interstate 90]] connect travelers to Erie from [[Boston, Massachusetts]] and points east, and from [[Cleveland, Ohio]] and points west. Those traveling north to Erie on [[Interstate 79]] can either merge with Interstate 90 or continue north for several local Erie exits before the road merges into the Bayfront Parkway in downtown Erie. Southbound travelers of Interstate 79 can connect with [[Interstate 80]] for points east to New Jersey or west to [[Akron, Ohio]] or [[Youngstown, Ohio]], or continue south on Interstate 79 to [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]] and [[Charleston, West Virginia]]. [[Interstate 86 (east)|Interstate 86]], also called the "Southern Tier Expressway," splits from Interstate 90 at [[North East, Pennsylvania]] and heads southeast through New York State to [[Binghamton, New York|Binghamton]].
 
The city has several [[arterial road]]s. [[Pennsylvania Route 5]] (12th Street), [[U.S. Route 20]] (26th Street and Buffalo Road), and 38th Street are major east-west routes through Erie's municipal roadway [[Grid plan|grid]]. The town is divided east from west at [[State Street]], a major thoroughfare in downtown Erie. [[U.S. Route 19]] is a major southwesterly route from downtown to a shopping area north of Interstate 90 known to locals as [[Peach Street|Upper Peach Street]].

[[Image:intermodal.JPG|thumb|The Intermodal Transportation Center at the end of Holland Street]]The [[Erie Metropolitan Transit Authority]] (EMTA) operates local and regional bus service seven days a week. A new city bus terminal opened in 2006. Connections are available to water taxi, rail services, and the airport. The Intermodal Transportation Center, which opened in 2002 at the Holland Street Pier, includes a commercial bus terminal. [[Greyhound Lines]] and [[Trailways Transportation System|Fullington Trailways (owned by Fullington Auto Bus Company)]] provide daily bus service, including routes with local stops between Erie and [[DuBois, Pennsylvania|DuBois]] and [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]], with connections to other destinations.<ref name="multiple"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ridesforallpa.com/getting_there.htm|title=Intercity Bus Service in Pennsylvania|publisher=The Transportation Advocacy Project|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref>

The former "Water Level Route" of the [[New York Central]] Railroad (now the [[CSX]] mainline) travels directly through Erie. This is a major mainline for the railroad and sees scores of trains a day. The mainline of the [[Norfolk Southern]] Railroad at one time ran directly down the middle of 19th Street in the city. Norfolk Southern decided to remove the 19th Street tracks in 1998.<ref>{{cite news| author=Hofius, Sarah| coauthors=Piet, Elizabeth| date=[[2005-06-08]]| publisher=Erie Times-News| url=http://www.goerie.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20050608/FRONTPAGE/506080368&SearchID=73285370706681| title=Residents track changes along old railroad line|accessdate=2007-06-26}}</ref> The 19th Street rail traffic is now routed onto the aforementioned transcontinental mainline. [[Amtrak]]'s [[Lake Shore Limited]] arrives at the [[Union Station (Erie)|Union Station]], in downtown Erie, twice daily.  Although there has been much discussion in recent years in favor of adding trains along the southern shore of [[Lake Erie]] to link [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]] with [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]], and beyond, although there are no plans to begin this service.

[[Image:Lastdc9ERI.jpg|thumb|left|The last [[DC-9]] to fly for [[US Air]] arriving at [[KERI|Erie International Airport]]]]
[[Erie International Airport]] ([[International Air Transport Association|IATA]]: ERI; [[International Civil Aviation Organization|IACO]]: KERI), located 5&nbsp;miles (8&nbsp;[[kilometre|km]]) southwest of the city, hosts [[general aviation]], charter, and scheduled [[airline]] service. Airlines  serving Erie include [[Delta Air Lines]], [[Continental Airlines]], [[US Airways]] and [[Northwest Airlines]]. Tom Ridge Field was recognized by the [[Pennsylvania]] Department of Transportation as the fastest-growing airport in the state and by the US Department of Transportation as the 3rd fastest-growing airport in the United States in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|author=Carroll, Jim | publisher=Erie International Airport|url=http://www.goerie.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/99999999/ERIEAIR_NEWS/50304068|title=Erie International 3rd in nation for increased passenger departures | date = [[March 04]] [[2005]] |accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref><ref name="multiple"/>

The Port of Erie is in Presque Isle Bay, a natural harbor formed by [[Presque Isle]]. The [[Port authority|Erie-Western Pennsylvania Port Authority]] provides [[Water taxi|water-taxi service]] in the summer months between Dobbins Landing and Liberty Park in downtown Erie, and the Waterworks ferry landing on Presque Isle.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The Port of Erie|url=http://www.porterie.org/transit_map_lg.gif|title= Bayfront Transportation Systems|title=Erie Bayfront Transportation System|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref>

A channel on the east side of Presque Isle allows ships to transit between the bay and Lake Erie. Cruise line services land at a dock at the Intermodal Transportation Center on the Holland Street Pier. A ''Great American Waterways'' cruise makes a 15-day run from Chicago to [[Warren, Rhode Island]], with a stop in Erie on the eastern leg of the journey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatlakescruising.com/mariner-prince/american-waterways.php|title=Great American Waterways| publisher = Great Lakes Cruise Company|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref> The Great Lakes Cruise Company and the American Canadian Cruise Line advertise this cruise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accl-smallships.com/Cruise_Details.cfm?Cruise_ID=39|title=Great American Waterways 2007 | publisher = American Canadian Caribbean Line Itinerary|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref>

== Media ==
[[Image:Erietimes2.jpg|thumb|right|The Erie Times&ndash;News main office]]
{{main|Media in Erie, Pennsylvania}}
Erie is served in print by [[Erie Times-News|The Erie Times-News]], the city's only daily newspaper. Erie has several alternative weekly and monthly publications.

Erie is ranked as the 142nd largest television market by Nielsen Media Research.<ref>{{citeweb|publisher=Time Warner|url=http://www.cablemediasales.com/pages/mkts/?cp=mkts&sp=dma&dma=eri|title=Erie DMA|accessdate=2007-05-25}}</ref> The market is served by stations affiliated with major American networks including [[WICU|WICU 12]] (NBC), [[WJET|WJET 24]] (ABC), [[WFXP|WFXP 66]] (FOX), [[WSEE|WSEE 35]] (CBS), and [[WBEP]] (CW). [[WQLN|WQLN 54]] is a member of PBS. Several Cleveland stations can be seen in the area. Erie is also served by over 25 AM and FM radio stations directly, and dozens of other stations are heard from elsewhere.

== Sister cities ==
As of June 2007, Erie has four official [[Town twinning|sister cities]] as designated by [[Sister Cities International]]:<ref>{{cite web|last=Miller|first=George| date=[[2007-03-24]]| url=http://www.goerie.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070324/NEWS02/703240354&SearchID=73277773742235| publisher=Erie Times-News| title=Erie adds Irish Sister City|accessdate=2007-05-21}}</ref>
* {{flagicon|Ireland}} - [[Dungarvan]], [[Ireland]]
* {{flagicon|Poland}} - [[Lublin]], [[Poland]]
* {{flagicon|Mexico}} - [[Merida]], [[Yucatan]], [[Mexico]]
* {{flagicon|China}} - [[Zibo]], [[China]]

